- `changedetectionio/blueprint/ui/static/js/modal.js`
- `changedetectionio/validate_url.py`

---

## Description

### 1. Stored XSS via Double Entity Decoding in Confirmation Modal

The clear history button uses a `data-confirm-message` attribute containing hardcoded HTML tags mixed with the Jinja2-escaped watch URL. When the browser parses HTML attributes, it decodes HTML entities. The `modal.js` library then reads this attribute and inserts it directly into `innerHTML` without escaping, causing a second layer of entity decoding. An attacker who controls the watch URL can inject HTML entity-encoded payloads that survive Jinja2 auto-escaping and URL validation, ultimately executing arbitrary JavaScript in the victim's browser (CWE-79).

### 2. Vulnerable Code Location â€” Template Sink

The vulnerability originates at `changedetectionio/blueprint/ui/templates/edit.html:553`:

```html
<a href="{{url_for('ui.clear_watch_history', uuid=uuid)}}"
   class="pure-button button-error"
   data-requires-confirm
   data-confirm-type="warning"
   data-confirm-title="{{ _('Clear History?') }}"
   data-confirm-message="<p>{{ _('Are you sure you want to clear all history for:') }}</p><p><strong>{{ watch.get('url', 'this watch') }}</strong></p><p>{{ _('This will remove all snapshots and previous versions. This action cannot be undone.') }}</p>"
   data-confirm-button="{{ _('Clear History') }}">{{ _('Clear History') }}</a>
```

The watch URL is rendered via `{{ watch.get('url', 'this watch') }}` inside an HTML attribute that contains literal `<p>` and `<strong>` tags. This placement defeats Jinja2 auto-escaping because the value is embedded in an HTML attribute that will later be read by JavaScript and re-inserted into the DOM.

### 3. Vulnerable Code Location â€” Client-Side Sink

`modal.js` reads the `data-confirm-message` attribute and inserts it directly into `innerHTML` without escaping:

```javascript
// modal.js â€” auto-attach handler
$(document).ready(function() {
  $(document).on('click', 'a[data-requires-confirm], button[data-requires-confirm]', function(e) {
    e.preventDefault();
    const $element = $(this);
    const config = {
      type: $element.attr('data-confirm-type') || 'danger',
      title: $element.attr('data-confirm-title') || _modalT('confirmTitle', 'Confirm Action'),
      message: $element.attr('data-confirm-message') || _modalT('proceedMessage', '<p>Are you sure you want to proceed?</p>'),
      confirmText: $element.attr('data-confirm-button') || _modalT('confirm', 'Confirm'),
      cancelText: $element.attr('data-cancel-button') || _modalT('cancel', 'Cancel'),
      onConfirm: function() { ... }
    };
    ModalDialog.confirm(config);
  });
});

// modal.js â€” ModalDialog.confirm (line 68)
dialog.innerHTML = `
  <div class="modal-header">
    ...
  </div>
  <div class="modal-body" id="modal-body">
    ${config.message}
  </div>
  ...
`;
```

A `_modalEscapeHTML` function exists in `modal.js` but is only used in the `confirmDelete` and `confirmUnlink` methods, not in the generic `confirm` path used by the auto-attach handler.

### 4. Double Decoding Attack Chain

The attack exploits two layers of HTML entity decoding:

1. **Template rendering**: Jinja2 auto-escapes the watch URL. For a URL containing `&lt;`, the template output in the HTML attribute becomes `&amp;lt;`.
2. **Browser attribute parsing**: When the browser parses the rendered HTML, it decodes HTML entities in attribute values. `&amp;lt;` becomes `&lt;` in the DOM attribute.
3. **innerHTML insertion**: `modal.js` reads the attribute value (`&lt;`) and inserts it into `innerHTML`. The browser parses the `innerHTML` string and decodes entities again: `&lt;` becomes `<`, `&gt;` becomes `>`, creating a real DOM element.

### 5. Bypassing URL Validation

The URL validator in `changedetectionio/validate_url.py:230-232` blocks raw `<` and `>` characters:

```python
if re.search(r'[<>]', test_url):
    logger.warning(f'URL "{test_url}" contains suspicious characters')
    return False
```

This prevents URLs containing literal `<script>` tags but does **not** block HTML entity references such as `&lt;`. A URL like `http://example.com#&lt;img/src=x/onerror=alert(1)&gt;` contains no raw `<` or `>` characters and passes validation. The `normalize_url_encoding` function preserves `&` and `;` in fragments, and `validators.url` accepts it as a valid URL.

### 6. No Content-Security-Policy Mitigation

The base template (`changedetectionio/templates/base.html`) does not set any `Content-Security-Policy` header. No `X-Frame-Options` or similar security headers are configured to mitigate inline event handler execution.

### 7. Persistence and Impact

The watch URL is persisted in the datastore via the API (`changedetectionio/api/Watch.py:475`) and UI forms. The stored malicious URL affects all authenticated users who visit the watch's edit page and click the clear history button. The edit page is accessible via `/edit/<uuid>` protected by `login_optionally_required`.

